b. Made.

(1) The imperfect subjunctive is used with pmusquam, antequam, pridiequam, in constructions where the earlier writers would have used the perfect indicative:

ante paucas quam obiret menses, Galia 8; pridiequam periret, Galia. bl.

(2) The subjunctive is once used with iubere:

lectis codicillis quibus ut id faceret iubebatur, Tib. 22.

(3) Suetonius is fond oi the iterative subjunctive in tem- poral and conditional clauses:

attollensque introiret, Galia. 73 quotiens exoscularetur, Catia. 33; promptus utique si perorandum ln aliquem esset, Galia. 53.

(4) As in Tacitus, the subjunctive is used in clauses introduced by tamquam and attasi to express the ground of action, without necessarily implying any suggestion oi un· reality ε
